The Bercen Inc. ? Denham Springs Facility's Prevention Program is composed of the following elements, which are all part of the Process Safety Management (PSM) program. This program follows the requirements set forth in 29 CFR 1910.119: 

1) Employees participate in the elements of this safety and release prevention program wherever possible; 

2) Training is provided for operators and maintenance personnel; 

3) Process Safety Information (PSI) is maintained on ammonia hazards and the ammonia system equipment; 

4) A Process Hazard Analysis(PHA) of the ammonia system was conducted and will be periodically reviewed to ensure adequacy of controls; 5) The Mechanical Integrity program ensures the system continues to operate as designed; 

6) Operating and Maintenance procedures provide operators and maintenance staff the information necessary to safely operate and maintain the system; 

7) Contractors working on or near the ammonia system are selected for safety performance, and are briefed on the hazards and safety requirements of the job; 

8) Hot Work Permits are required whenever welding, cutting, grinding or other activities are conducted that could generate sparks and start a fire; 

9) The Management of Change(MOC) program requires that the impact of changes to the ammonia system be evaluated and approved prior to the work being conducted; 

10) Pre-Startup Safety Reviews(PSSR) are conducted prior to restart of the system after modifications to ensure that impacts of the change are addressed; 

11) Incident investigations are conducted for incidents involving ammonia releases and near misses that endanger employees or the public, if such an incident were to occur; 

12) Compliance Audits will be conducted every three years to ensure that the prevention program is meeting its objectives; 

13) Emergency Planning and Response ensures that employees are advised of evacuation routes, assembly areas, and responsibilities in the event of an anhydrous ammonia release; and 

14) Trade Secrets utilized in the manufacturing process at the facility do not interfere with the dissemination of pertinent PSM information about the covered process to operators, employees and/or the general public.
